<user>114183143603142724217</user><resp>None</resp><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Text>
Came here for dinner followed by a comedy show. I thought I'd try the BUNNY CHOW, both because of the name, and also because it sounded the most uniquely South African. I heard it's quite popular in Durban. Well, when they tell you that you have a loaf of bread filled with curry, I imagined something like a baguette or bread bowl. Something round and crusty. Nope, this was like a proper store-bought loaf of bread with a hole dug out the middle!
It was yummy, and I think everyone else around me enjoyed their dinners as well.
The comedy show was fun, too!
Casual atmosphere, kind of a random location out by the furniture stores!< /Text>

1436723876970</date>
<rating>1< /rating>< Review>
Got out with a very bad taste...

I visited Capetown several times in the past now. Had been there yesterday. I must say that the food there is great, but the service is poor and we will never come back. I made an order with the waiter and specifically pointed with my finger to the dishes I ordered, because once an error was made with my order. The waiter did not write the order on paper and brought me one dish twice instead of once. When I complained, the waiter said he will check and never came back. I went to the register to ask, and the person in charge (possibly the owner) replied "I remember you. You came here 4 times. You once made a mistake with a dish costing $24. This time you will pay in full." I was appalled by this treatment and by the public humiliation. Needless to say, I will never come back, and I advise you to do the same.</Review>

<Time>1450496410459< /Time><Text>Dinner on Friday night. Casual, upbeat atmosphere and helpful, personable service. The peri-peri wings (one of several items featuring this peppery, flavorful sauce) are a wonderful place to start exploring the varied menu. Meat pies are savory with a little spice, and pair well with thick-cut fries infused with malt vinegar and salt. The brandy tart is tremendous: crisp, but with a cake-like texture and soaked with a brandy sauce and topped with caramelized sugar. Make sure you have someone to share it with you.

Great experience. Will be coming back. Tomorrow.<//Text><username>Jesse Tingle< /username><GmapID>0x80dbf8b5423065d5:0x588f01d61800651f</GmapID>< Pictures>

< rating>
5</rating>
<review>So you know. They are changing their name officially in October, but already have the signage that has the current/old name. It will now be called something like the Malt Bar or something similar.

They are under new ownership, but they told me they are keeping a lot of their current South African fusion recipes. That makes me happy since I about Ely LOVE their peri peri wings and chicken quarters! Beware, they are pretty hot, but soooo worth the pain! If I were to host a party that warranted chicken wings, I would order these for it when I wanted something different.

Their desserts are also in point. I have tried all of them in the past, and I have to say their brandy tart is my favorite. They give you a generous amount, too, and is easily shared between about 2-3 people.

Seriously, if you want to try something different, this restaurant is a great place to go in the Miramar area. They don't disappoint< /review>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

<username>Zed Star< /username><Date>1501187114226< /Date><rating>1< /rating><Text>My wife and a few of her co-workers came here for lunch today as they have done a few times before.My wife phoned me to ask if I wanted her to pick up a few frozen pies or pasties for home and I said sure pick up half a dozen.So I checked out their website to remind myself of their varieties and decided on a ground beef curry pie,a steak & kidney pie and a spinach and feta pastie.My wife would have added 3 chicken variety pasties to make up the order of 6.We ended up with 2 cornish pasties because they had bugger all of anything frozen ready to sell.And I just found out that the founders and owners of the business Graham and his lovely wife Mary-Louise are no longer involved with Cape Town in any way.I wonder if the no frozen chicken pies and pasties has anything to do with a customer recently getting food poisoning from a chicken pie.Hopefully the quality of the products and the friendly service we used to get won't go down the gurgler now new owners are in the mix.We've been customers for donkey years but being an ex-pat Aussie I'm only interested in the pies.So when these guys have only 2 or 3 varieties of pies & pasties to choose from instead of their whole range you have to wonder what's going on.It never would have happened when Graham and Mary-Louise were running the show.So I phoned up and complained and the girl Natalia didn't have a clue what was going on.And when I spoke to some arrogant dude named Gary who called himself the manager or something he gave me a pathetic excuse they were making some more pies now.Not much good to me now mate.You guys better get your act together or you'll be moving down the food chain.</Text>< Pictures>

<rate>5<//rate>< time>
1499752773957< /time>
<Text>Love, love, love the NEW owner of CapeTown Restaurant - welcoming, friendly, (...what a pleasant change from previous owner!)

We had a table of 17, great service & the food came out hot. Everyone had their South African favorite. The steak sandwich I had was awesome & I can highly recommend the signature lamb curry.  We had two vegetarian family members who enjoyed the vegetable bunny chows & the potato samosas (off the Sampler Platter). The Sampler Platter is a good deal - a taste of most of the popular South African foods - meat pie, sausage roll, boerewors, & peri peri chicken. On the gourmet chicken & mushroom pie I overheard the comment,  "I want one of these pies every day!"

My son in law enjoyed the beer on tap & for me the vanilla cream soda on tap is a great substitute for the "original" South African Spar-letta cream soda.

I'll definitely be back soon for the Sample Platter & to try out new dishes that are going to be added to the menu.</Text>< name>
Oonagh Morley</name>

This atmosphere is really nice here.  The employees are very friendly.  We had the meat platter, but they were out of the lamb which we really wanted to taste.  We want to go back to try the meat pies.  We went late, and per other reviews they run out, so we didn't even ask.  We had the peri wings, and they were ok.  Samossas were amazing and the sauce it came with it was delicious.  We will go again a little earlier for the meat pies, and more samoosas.</text>

< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< Time>
1459734869608<//Time>
< Rating>
5<//Rating>
<text>Lamb wrap with slap chips, glass of chenin blanc.

This is one of my favorite meals in San Diego. I work nearby, so I find myself gravitating to Cape Town quite frequently. The lamb wrap is a lamb-curry burrito, with potatoes and rice. If you're interested for a really unique flavor, ask for a bottle of their peri-peri sauce. Their peri-peri sauce has got a good heat, and very distinct taste.  I love a good potato side, and the slap chips are pretty awesome. They're like thick potato wedges with a soft interior, with a touch of vinegar.

It's got distinctive culture. It's well decorated, and has a market (snacks, wines, and souvenirs) at the side of the restaurant. You often hear some South African accents who come to have some of their native cuisine.

They've also got some interesting programs. As a regular, I use their loyalty program. I think they're also doing deliveries, but I can't attest to that personally.

Definitely check out their lamb wrap and their peri-peri sauce. Also great: half-chicken with side salad (really good deal), peri peri chicken salad (a healthy option for when you've had too much of their lamb wrap)! I've gotten a number of my coworkers hooked on the lamb wrap; it's a solid plate.</text>< response>
None<//response>

Unfortunately, even though this charger is listed on Chargepoint and PlugShare as available, it is not operational. When I went in for assistance, I was greeted with total indifference and a couple of excuses. When I used to work behind a counter, I would at least go online and see if I could find a solution for a customer. But not here at First Nissan. One salesman suggested that I could go over to the Chevy dealership and see if they could help me. Another salesman made an excuse:"well, we didn't even have the charger last month". Yes, and in that case I wouldn't have planned my trip around it since it wouldn't have been listed as installed and operational. I know that things happen and that chargers go offline, but the thing that disappointed me was that these sales fellows just didn't care. Wasn't their problem. <date>1463615413748< /date><rate>1</rate><Review>This review is about 1st Nissan service department! Over four years ago I moved to Simi Valley, and have been bringing my Nissan vehicle to 1st Nissan Simi Valley service department every 5,000 to 6,000 miles for routine maintenance, there was one recall issue, and also had a front window washer unit replaced. 1st Nissan became my go-to place for service. BUT NEVER AGAIN WILL I USE THEM. Here is why: Something changed with this service department over the past 6 months. They now seem to operate on a corrupt line of practice as you hear so often of so many other automotive service shops. They make claims of bogus problems that simply do not exist. I am sure they make a lot of up-sells $$$ on people that are naÃ¯ve or simply do not know enough about cars and who fall prey to these tactics, but I have worked on all my cars most of my life from changing my own brakes, plugs and fluids to replacing timing belts to replacing entire engines. 6 Months ago I brought my vehicle in for routine maintenance, oil change, tire rotation and even asked them to change out all my air filters. The price was reasonable and I approved the work. When I came to pick up the vehicle the service agent told me there were two serious issues that needed immediate attention or could create a dangerous situation if left unrepaired. He told me that one of my engine motor mounts was broken, and that my timing belt was making noise and that both needed to be replaced (Total cost for both in excess of $1900). Many customers would probably trust the agent and likely pay for the â€œNeeded repairsâ€ and not think twice. I said I would have to think about it before I approved the work (Believe me, if I discovered the vehicle needed those repairs I would have done so). Of course I examined both and found nothing wrong, I even took my vehicle to a friend who is a mechanic and he confirmed that there was absolutely nothing wrong with either. Today 05/16/16 I again took my vehicle in for oil change, tire rotations, and also asked them to clean up the battery which had a little corrosion on the terminals, and (Also asked them to determine why my window washer reservoir was not holding fluid). I've never had a barber exercise the perfection every step of the way as did Jeff. This guys the real deal and I don't plan on going anywhere else for a haircut. I finally found a barber.

He's honestly the mad scientist of cutting hair. You know how the greats zone out and just accomplish their task with absolute precision. Ya, that's this guy. Very detail oriented, perfectionist style cutting.

You can tell he's intensely focused on doing everything right at a high professional level. Most barbers are very distracted but it seems as if this guy went through military style barbering camp where your life depends on perfecting haircuts or something.

< text>
This was THE WORST nail salon experience I've ever had! Wish I could actually rate them with 0 stars. The salon was not very busy when I arrived and I was able to be seated immediately. I proceeded to choose a polish color from the wall and sit down. I was almost instantly bombarded with the questions about "gel" color instead of polish. I don't see the need to pay $15 EXTRA for "gel" color, as I typically never have chipped polish... and IF I do, being a licensed cosmetologist, I can fix them myself. She kept insisting that I NEEDED "gel". Besides the point. A different tech came over and assisted in selecting a "gel" color as close to the polish color I chose as she could find. I selected a completely different color from the "gel" colors I was shown. The tech proceeded to file and buff my nails and she asked again if I wanted "gel".  I said "let's see what my nails look like after you clean them up, I may just leave them clear". She IMMEDIATELY became very nasty and aggressive. Snatching and pushing my fingers as she moved along. 2 other customers walked in, and she proceeded to rush through the rest of my service. Almost as if she was annoyed that I came in to begin with. She asked again "so clear, or polish?" Suddenly, the same "gel" she insisted I needed wasn't an option, as she was trying to hurry me out to help the next customers that came in. I said "don't worry about it!" She quickly slathered some clear polish on my nails and said "thank you" although her a tone indicated more of "please get out of here, you're wasting my time". I paid exactly what she quoted me, $20 and left.

Here's the issue with a lot of these establishments... people of color are second rate customers. I can't possibly want to have the same level of service as other people, therefore I must never tip. Well, you assumed wrong, as THIS is the first time I've ever received a service and not left a tip. If I'm not good enough for your service, then surely, I'd prefer to take my money elsewhere.

You've got to do better, ladies. You don't treat paying customers like trash. Have a great day!< /text>

< text>
We found this place on Yelp and it is such a cool building. The atmosphere is great but $35 for a 16" pizza is crazy, in my opinion. We ordered a medium pizza, small salad, a sandwich, and 2 drinks for $53. My husband loved his sandwich, Meatball Grinder, but the balsamic dressing for my Strawberry with Feta Salad was so potent that I asked for a different dressing which I was told it would cost extra. That was a bummer that they charge to replace the crummy dressing that came with it.  I really liked the crispy onions on the pizza but the smoked flavor was overwhelming, 1 piece was more than enough for me. I loved the building and ambience more than the food so I probably won't be back but who knows.<//text>

<user_name>Fred Reed</user_name>< Date>
1544063885970< /Date>
<rate>1< /rate>< review>
I went to the Planing Mill today for lunch.  I got there about 1:45pm.  I looked through the menu and wanted to stay but the only other patrons were at the bar.  I change my mind and got a slice togo.  I took it to my car with a soda.  The Pizza was completely dried out.  The crust was hard on the bottom and thick and chewy in the middle.  The tip of the slice was pointing up.  The cheese was hard and completely dried out.  I returned to the Pizzeria and waited at the counter.  The cashier came back from the bar in a few minutes and I told her the Pizza was dried and old.  She went directly to the phone and started dialing.  She never looked at it or acknowledged anything.  I gave her back the Pizza and she said she was contacting her manager.  I decided just to leave.  She knew the pizza was old and dried up when she sold it to me.  Seriously $9.00 ($7.50 plus tip) for a slice that Costco ($1.50) would have thrown out.  More importantly they knew they gave me awful pizza and never apologized.  Don't bother there are plenty of good Pizzerias around don't support rotten service, I'm not the only one who have seen this.</review>

< review>
Clean place with good food. You seat yourself and order at the counter when you're ready to order. Lots of seating if you're thinking of bringing a lot of people and a wheelchair could fit at the end of the table if need be. They have highchairs for babies too. They have a small bar in one corner but it's a healthy atmosphere and a good place for families. The staff was polite.</review>

<gmap_id>0x80952f7a594ffb55:0x3e88a089ccbf3b5a</gmap_id><Time>1527774877293<//Time>< Text>
Went here with a group of 10. The hostess was nice and friendly. We didn't have much if a wait but it was a Wednesday evening and there were graduation groups eating there at the time.
SERVICE: The service was pretty good. She took our drink orders right away and we got the drinks quickly. My complaint here is that the server didn't come back after we got our drinks to ask about refills on our beers or sodas.
FOOD: The food was great too. I made a custom pizza and about half of our table got personal pizzas while the rest got a salad or sandwich. No complaints from the others in my group about their food. I tried a few of the other items that my family had. The meatball sandwich was good but lacked the flavor to make it great. The 3 pig pizza with onion straws on it was just too much stuff on one pizza and was difficult to eat. Flavor wise it was pretty good though.
One of my other complaints is the open layout coupled with the concrete floor makes it very loud and hard to hear people across the table. I'd go back though and try some of the other dishes on the menu. Maybe try to go back when it's not as busy though or at on of the outdoor tables.</Text>

< Text>
I love this place! Their pizza is some of the best I've had outside of NY and the toppings combinations are pretty great. Their various appetizers are also quite good (I recommend the wings and drunken mushrooms). In addition to all the great food they serve, they also have a pretty nice, albeit a little small, craft beer bar. With up to a dozen beers that rotate out every few days, there's always something new to try. If you're in the Visalia area and looking for something to eat, you can't go wrong stopping by here.< /Text>

Great little pizza spot! I don't visit Visalia very often, but I'll definitely be back. It's tucked in a random little spot. Super rustic and fun. They have an outdoor patio. <Text>I went this afternoon with some friends.  I have been to the Planing Mill before and have always had wonderful food, and no issues with service before today.  My friends and I each ordered personal pizzas and drinks.  I ordered the Muscles from Brussels, with no bacon.  I had been planning on ordering this pizza since we decided where we would be having lunch.  It sounded awesome, and I have heard that Mike's Hot Honey is amazing. Unfortunately, when my pizza arrived, I was told that they were out of the honey.  I was visibly disappointed and told our server that the only reason I ordered that pizza was because of the honey.  She was incredibly polite and apologized, and I appreciate that, but I wish that I had been told before hand that they were out of the honey.  I 100% would have ordered a different pizza.  That particular pizza has only 6 toppings and now I'm down 2.  The server offered to bring me a different sauce on the side, but I wasn't sure what to order.  She suggested the aioli that is typically paired with the appetizers.  I don't know that that was the right choice.  As I said, the server was very sweet, and very apologetic, my issue is that I felt like I was being offered a substutution for an ingredient, but there was no offer to "make it right" or make sure I was satisfied with what I got.  Other establishments would have offered a replacement, or perhaps a discount on my next visit, something....  But that was not the case.  Additionally, when we went to the bar, we were interested in trying the Mexican lager that was on the $2 Taco Tuesday special, but the bartender wasn't happy with the way it was pouring, so we were offered a different beer, at the same price.  The second beer wasn't as good, but for $2 it was a decent replacement.  This was the offer to make it right that I had hoped for with the pizza.  I will definitely be back, but I will be sure to ask if all the ingredients are available before I order my pizza.<//Text><Rating>3< /Rating></record>
